    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gummies for Skin</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Do skin gummies actually work?</summary><p>Yes, for clinically studied ingredients at adequate doses. Collagen peptides (2.5-10g) improve elasticity and wrinkle depth in 11 RCTs. Hyaluronic acid (120-240mg) improves moisture. Vitamin C is essential for collagen synthesis. Results require 8-12 weeks of consistent use.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best vitamin for glowing skin?</summary><p>Vitamin C — essential for collagen synthesis, antioxidant, inhibits melanin (brightening). Vitamin E works synergistically with C (4x protection together). Vitamin A promotes cell turnover. Biotin supports skin cell regeneration. A combination provides the most comprehensive support.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long do skin gummies take to show results?</summary><p>Skin cells turn over every 28 days. Hydration improvements at 4-6 weeks. Elasticity and wrinkle improvements at 8-12 weeks. Continued improvement through 24 weeks. Antioxidant protection builds gradually. Consistent daily use is essential.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take collagen or hyaluronic acid?</summary><p>Both serve different functions: collagen provides structural firmness, HA provides hydration (holds 1,000x its weight in water). For comprehensive skin support, take both. Products combining both are most efficient.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can gummies replace my skincare routine?</summary><p>No. Gummies work from the inside (collagen synthesis, antioxidant defense). Topical skincare works from the outside (direct surface treatment). The most effective approach combines both: internal supplementation + external skincare (sunscreen, retinoids, moisturizers).</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are skin gummies safe for all skin types?</summary><p>Yes. Oral supplements work through internal pathways and do not contact skin directly. Safe for oily, dry, combination, and sensitive skin. Check collagen sources for fish/shellfish allergies. Consult a dermatologist if you have autoimmune skin conditions.</p></details>

